          <avActivityHighlights>The danger of moist and wet avalanches will increase quickly during the day.</avActivityHighlights>
          <avActivityComment>Early morning: The surface of the snowpack will only just freeze. Where cloud cover will be heaviest during the night. &lt;br/&gt; From late morning the natural activity of avalanches will increase. &lt;br/&gt; In particular in starting zones where no previous releases have taken place and on very steep slopes more medium-sized and, in isolated cases, large natural wet avalanches are possible. &lt;br/&gt; The conditions are generally favourable for ski touring. Backcountry tours and ascents to alpine cabins should be concluded timely. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; In the course of the day mostly small wind slabs will form especially above approximately 3000 m.</avActivityComment>
          <snowpackStructureComment>The wind will be moderate in some localities. &lt;br/&gt; The weather conditions gave rise to rapid settling of the snowpack. &lt;br/&gt; At higher altitudes, snow cover becomes thinner and patchy; it is better at mid-altitudes, which are less exposed to the wind. Below approximately 2000 m hardly any snow is lying. &lt;br/&gt; The weather conditions gave rise to moistening of the snowpack below approximately 2500 m. &lt;br/&gt; Weak layers exist in the snowpack in particular on steep shady slopes.</snowpackStructureComment>
          <tendencyComment>More moist and wet avalanches are possible. &lt;br/&gt; As a consequence of the moderate northwesterly wind, fresh snow drift accumulations will form.</tendencyComment>
        </BulletinMeasurements>
      </bulletinResultsOf>
